---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="manifesto - embody.tools"
  description="Why TouchDesigner should be transparent, diffable, and built faster alongside your AI agent."
>
  <section class="page-section manifesto-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">manifesto</p>
    <h1>Build faster, in the open</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Everything is moving faster now. Everyone is shipping. We&rsquo;re entering a new era in
      digital media, and TouchDesigner is positioned to become one of the leading
      platforms of content creation. Embody exists to help our community build faster and
      better than ever &mdash; open source, no strings attached, nothing SaaSy.
    </p>
  </section>

  <article class="page-section tight manifesto-body">
    <p>
      The gap between what an artist imagines and what&rsquo;s on their screen is where almost every
      creative project has died. Not because they gave up, but because the
      cost of executing it was higher than the cost of moving on. Embody exists to collapse
      that gap.
    </p>

    <h2>Forward velocity</h2>

    <p>
      The first move is forward velocity. <strong>Envoy</strong> is an MCP server that lets
      your AI assistant build inside your live TouchDesigner session. Say what you want
      &mdash; &ldquo;give me a noise-driven particle system that reacts to audio&rdquo; &mdash;
      and watch the operators appear, wired up, named, annotated, laid out. Not a screenshot
      of a network. Not a code snippet to paste. The actual network, in front of you, ready
      to play with. Idea to first version in seconds.
    </p>

    <p>
      But forward velocity by itself is a trap. Generative tools that only go forward are
      tools that lock you in. You ask the model for a thing, you get a thing, and now you&rsquo;re
      stuck with a thing &mdash; because the cost of trying a different approach is starting
      over. That&rsquo;s not flow. That&rsquo;s a fancier kind of friction.
    </p>

    <h2>Lateral velocity</h2>

    <p>
      So the second move is lateral velocity. <strong>Embody</strong> externalizes every
      operator to files on disk. Branch off the version that&rsquo;s almost right. Restore
      yesterday&rsquo;s state on the next project open. See exactly what changed from a week
      ago. Hand the agent a snapshot of what&rsquo;s currently on the screen and ask it to
      riff. Every direction you&rsquo;d want to move costs about as much as deciding to move
      there.
    </p>

    <h2>A format the network can live in</h2>

    <p>
      Both of these depend on a quiet third thing: a <strong>format the network can live in
      as text</strong>. A <code>.toe</code> file is a black box &mdash; your AI agent can&rsquo;t
      see inside it, your diff tool can&rsquo;t read it, your filesystem can&rsquo;t store one
      version of it next to another. TDN is what lets the network exist as something the agent
      and the artist can both work on. Without it, none of the rest of this is possible. With
      it, every step of the loop &mdash; generate, compare, revert, branch &mdash; runs at the
      speed of typing.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        The tool keeps up with you, instead of the other way around.
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      What this adds up to is a single promise: <strong>the tool keeps up with you, instead
      of the other way around</strong>. The forty-minute translation tax goes away. You stay
      in the room with the idea. The network is the conversation, not the homework after the
      conversation.
    </p>

    <p>
      That&rsquo;s what speed of thought looks like. It&rsquo;s not &ldquo;the AI did it for
      you.&rdquo; It&rsquo;s &ldquo;you didn&rsquo;t have to slow down.&rdquo;
    </p>

    <p>
      Embody is open source, runs entirely inside TouchDesigner, and works with Claude Code,
      Codex, Gemini CLI, Cursor, Windsurf, GitHub Copilot via VS Code, or any MCP-compatible
      client. Try it on a real idea you&rsquo;ve been putting off. See how far you get in an hour.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  /* Give the lede the same readable measure as the body and pull it tight to
     the hero so the essay reads as one continuous column. */
  .manifesto-hero .lede {
    max-width: 70ch;
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  /* The body neutralizes its own top padding, but the hero still carried a full
     section padding-bottom -- a huge lede->body gap. Drop it so the essay flows
     as one column (the body's tight top padding supplies the breathing room). */
  .manifesto-hero {
    padding-bottom: 0;
  }

  /* Headings stay lowercase to match the kicker and the site's lowercase voice
     ("see it. embody it."). Scoped to the manifesto's own headings so the body
     prose (TouchDesigner, Envoy, MCP, ...) keeps its proper casing. */
  .manifesto-hero h1 {
    text-transform: lowercase;
  }

  /* Single-column essay capped at a comfortable reading measure (~70ch). The
     body sits directly under the hero, so neutralize the section's own top
     padding and rely on paragraph rhythm instead. */
  .manifesto-body {
    max-width: 70ch;
    padding-top: clamp(1.75rem, 3vw, 2.5rem);
  }

  .manifesto-body p {
    margin: 0 0 1.4rem;
    color: var(--text);
    font-size: 1.08rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  /* Section subheads: display font, accent color, generous space above so each
     movement of the argument is clearly set off. */
  .manifesto-body h2 {
    margin: 2.6rem 0 1.1rem;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 2.4vw, 1.85rem);
    line-height: 1.15;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    text-transform: lowercase;
  }

  .manifesto-body strong {
    color: var(--text);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .manifesto-body a {
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  .manifesto-body a:hover {
    color: var(--accent-hover);
  }

  .manifesto-body code {
    background: var(--bg-code);
    border: 1px solid var(--border-faint);
    border-radius: 4px;
    padding: 0.05em 0.4em;
    color: var(--text);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.92em;
  }

  /* Pull quote: an accent rule on the left, display font, larger -- echoes the
     landing page's .pullquote treatment so the two manifesto surfaces feel of a
     piece. */
  .manifesto-body blockquote {
    margin: 2.4rem 0;
    padding: 0 0 0 1.75rem;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--accent);
  }

  .manifesto-body blockquote p {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--text);
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: clamp(1.3rem, 2.4vw, 1.85rem);
    line-height: 1.45;
    letter-spacing: -0.015em;
  }
</style>
